<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-04T18:11:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-04T18:11:00-05:00" n="274" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d274">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.91/12–451: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <persName type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in
                                        India</gloss>
                                </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d274fn1">Repeated to Karachi as telegram
                                    520, to Paris as <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> 336,
                                    and to London as 2778.</note>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-04T18:11:00-05:00">December 4, 1951—6:11 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1113. Re Kashmir. Dept appreciates views expressed <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 1911 Nov 29. (Rptd Karachi as
                                95, Paris <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> as 37, London as
                                62). In event Graham has not succeeded by Dec 22—due date his
                                    report<note n="2" xml:id="d274fn2">The U.N. Representative for
                                    India and Pakistan transmitted his second report to the Security
                                    Council on December 18, 1951 (U.N. document <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>/2448).</note>—we believe if parties
                                either tacitly or openly indicate a willingness for him continue and
                                    <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> does not specifically
                                terminate his services he cld continue his negots. Dept plans at
                                working level confer immed future with UK re possible courses action
                                in event Graham’s present efforts unsuccessful.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>